  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper/CLI (no React/frontend exists in this repo — fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notifiers), so I've mapped the requested categories onto their Python equivalents.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-73` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` issues one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, once per pipeline run:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nBoards like Amazon/Microsoft (`max_pages=40`, 10/page → up to 400 jobs) or a multi-source run easily hit thousands of individual round-trips per invocation. Fix: bulk-fetch existing hashes with one `IN (...)` query (chunked — SQLite caps bound parameters at 999), then diff in memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    new, changed = [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [job.key for job in jobs]\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    CHUNK = 500\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), CHUNK):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + CHUNK]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\", chunk\n        ).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/500), and lets SQLite do one indexed lookup instead of N separate statement preps.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:11-41`)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside** the per-job loop in `filter_jobs()`, so the same keyword list gets `re.compile`'d once for every job in the batch:\n\n```python\nreturn [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFix: compile once per run, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l in loc for l in locations):   # locations pre-lowered\n            return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if max_age := rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nCheap per-job today, but scales linearly with both job count and keyword count — worth fixing before `include_keywords`/`exclude_keywords` lists grow.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `Job.content_hash`/`key` recomputed (`models.py:55-69`, `store.py:76-97`)\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (sha256 over a joined string), not cached. In `diff()`, for the insert/changed path it gets computed once for the comparison (`job.content_hash`) and again inside `to_row()` when `_insert`/`_update` run — same for `key`. Because `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (no `__dict__`); simplest fix is to compute `to_row()` once per job and thread the dict through instead of recomputing:\n\n```python\nrow = job.to_row()  # computes key + content_hash once\nprev_hash = existing.get(row[\"key\"])\nif prev_hash is None:\n    new.append(job); self._insert(cur, row, now)\nelif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n    changed.append(job); self._update(cur, row, now)\nelse:\n    cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, row[\"key\"]))\n```\n(and change `_insert`/`_update` to take the row dict directly). Minor compared to #1, but free once you're already touching this function.\n\n### 4. Caching opportunities\n\n- **Synchronous notifiers** (`notify.py:33-99`): `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` each call `httpx.post(...)` directly, opening a fresh connection (TCP+TLS handshake) per call. Only 3 calls per run today, so low priority, but if you add more webhook-style notifiers, share one `httpx.Client()` across `dispatch()`.\n- **Meta fetcher** (`fetchers.py:537-574`) re-scrapes `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens from the careers HTML on every run — this is inherent to the site (no stable token TTL to cache against), not a bug.\n- No opportunity for a \"response cache\" in the fetchers themselves — this is a scraper whose job is to see *fresh* state every run, so caching HTTP responses would defeat the purpose. The dedup work is correctly pushed to the DB layer (fix #1 above is the real caching win here).\n\n### 5. Memory leaks — none found\n\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:767-788`) is closed in a `finally` only when it's owned by the function — correct, no leak.\n- `Store` is used as a context manager (`with Store(...) as store`) in `pipeline.py:42` and `agent.py:73/126` — connection is always closed.\n- Pagination loops (`twosigma`, `optiver`, `google`, `microsoft`, `netflix`, `amazon`, `workday`) all bound by `max_pages`/`total` — no unbounded accumulation.\n- `agent.py:219-228` temp file (`.ats.html`) is cleaned up via `unlink(missing_ok=True)` in a `finally` — correct even if Chrome fails.\n\n**Priority**: fix #1 (`Store.diff` N+1) first — it's the one with real, growing cost as job boards scale into the thousands; #2 is next since keyword lists will only grow; #3 is optional polish.\n",
